
Is there a keyboard shortcut in Windows for starting PowerShell or any command prompt?
ChatGPT

Yes, there is a keyboard shortcut in Windows for starting PowerShell or the Command Prompt. By default, you can use the following keyboard shortcut to open a command prompt window:

    Windows key + R: This keyboard shortcut opens the "Run" dialog. You can then type "cmd" and press Enter to open the Command Prompt window.

To open PowerShell specifically, you can use the following keyboard shortcut:

    Windows key + X, followed by C: Press the Windows key and the X key together to open the Power User Menu (also known as the Win+X menu), and then press the C key. This shortcut opens an elevated (admin) PowerShell window.

Alternatively, you can create your own custom keyboard shortcuts for PowerShell or the Command Prompt by creating shortcuts on your desktop or Start Menu and assigning them a shortcut key combination. Here's how:

    Right-click on an empty space on your desktop or in the Start Menu.

    Select "New" and then "Shortcut".

    In the "Create Shortcut" window, enter the following command for PowerShell or the Command Prompt:
        For PowerShell: powershell.exe
        For Command Prompt: cmd.exe

    Click "Next" and give the shortcut a name.

    Click "Finish" to create the shortcut.

    Right-click on the shortcut and select "Properties".

    In the "Properties" window, go to the "Shortcut" tab.

    Click in the "Shortcut key" field and press the keyboard shortcut you want to assign to the shortcut (e.g., Ctrl+Alt+P for PowerShell or Ctrl+Alt+C for Command Prompt).

    Click "OK" to save the changes.

Once you have assigned the shortcut keys, you can use them to quickly open PowerShell or the Command Prompt without going through the Start Menu or Run dialog.

